    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>'Too Much to Know'</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>John W O'Sullivan letter says 'there is simply too much to know' is poor excuse for justifying college seniors' ignorance of American history (July 6 letter)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I was aghast to read a July 6 letter  offering ''there is simply too much to know'' as a reason for the sobering lack of knowledge of college seniors on an American history quiz. Yet 16 years after college, I got all of the questions on the quiz correct.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I was aghast to read a July 6 letter  offering ''there is simply too much to know'' as a reason for the sobering lack of knowledge of college seniors on an American history quiz. Yet 16 years after college, I got all of the questions on the quiz correct.</p>
        <p>Americans should be aware of their country's history to function as citizens. Asserting that ''there is simply too much to know'' is a poor excuse for justifying ignorance.  JOHN W. O'SULLIVAN JR.  Yorktown Heights, N.Y., July 7, 2000</p>
      </block>
